article.description:
Grinning and leading cheers from the sideline, Alonzo Mourning and three other Miami Heat starters watched their
backups beat New York.
article.headline: Heat's fourth-quarter streaks too much for Knicks
article.linkText: Miami reserves get the job done in beating New York
article.story:
MIAMI (AP) -- Grinning and leading cheers from the sideline, Alonzo Mourning and three other Miami Heat starters watched their backups spark a rally that buried the New York Knicks. Miami scored the first 16 points of the fourth quarter and sank nine consecutive shots to overtake New York 100-86 Thursday night. The Heat's unlikely heroes included Chris Gatling, Vladimir Stepania and Anthony Carter. Starters Mourning, Brian Grant, Rod Strickland and Kendall Gill watched the surge from their seats. "We were over there having a ball, enjoying every minute of it," Mourning said. "We realize how hard those guys work in practice." Eddie Jones scored 32 points for the Heat, including 10 in the final period. "We had an absolute explosion in the fourth quarter," coach Pat Riley said. "It was unlike anything I've seen since last year." Miami has won 16 of 22, but is still eight games below .500 (24-32) as it tries to pull into contention for a playoff berth. The last-place Knicks lost their sixth in a row and blew a 74-67 lead to start the final period. "Another self-destruction," guard Allan Houston said. "It gets to the point where everybody is in disarray." A basket by Carter began Miami's run. Jones hit an acrobatic reverse layup, drew a foul and sank the free throw for a 74-all tie. Carter's free throw gave the Heat their first lead since the opening period at 75-74, and three baskets by Gatling helped push the lead to 83-74. "We played great defense, pushed the ball on the fastbreak, and the shots kept falling," Carter said. The Knicks missed six consecutive shots and committed three turnovers before Charlie Ward's 3-pointer ended the 16-0 run. "I can't figure out what goes on in their heads," Knicks coach Don Chaney said. "All I know is that we didn't respond to their intensity, and we got careless with the ball." Miami sank three more shots for a 91-77 lead and was 9-for-9 in the quarter before Stepania missed a dunk. The spurt reached 27-3 on another Gatling basket, putting Miami ahead 94-77. The comeback was especially sweet for Carter, who recently returned from hernia surgery and was booed during Miami's most recent home game. He had seven points and seven assists in 21 minutes. "He's a tough little kid," Riley said. "He's not going to let a few boos bother him." Miami, last in the NBA in scoring, reached 100 points for only the sixth time. Seven of New York's past 10 opponents have hit 100. Latrell Sprewell scored 22 points for New York. Houston scored 17 but missed 15 of 22 shots. Mourning picked up his second, third and fourth fouls early in the third period, then went to the bench, and Riley left him there in the fourth quarter. "The team was rolling and rolling and rolling and rolling," Riley said. "I didn't want to break that momentum." Mourning finished with seven points and six rebounds in 23 minutes. "Their bench really came through," Sprewell said. "You'd think with Zo out for that long, we could have taken advantage better, but we didn't." While Miami was playing for the second consecutive night, the Knicks had been off since Sunday and started quickly. They ran off eight consecutive points midway through the first half to lead 32-22, then stayed ahead until early in the fourth quarter. Game notes
Miami leads the season series 2-1 with one game remaining April 14. ... Since Jan. 1, Miami is 18-9 and New York is 7-18. ... The Knicks squandered a lead at the start of the final period for the 10th time.
